**No input validation on OID parameters**: `anchor_oid`, `reply_to_oid`, `comment_oid`, and `thread_id` are all accepted as raw `String` from the MCP client with no validation before being passed to git operations. While the underlying git-forge library may reject invalid OIDs, the error messages will be confusing git2 errors rather than clear MCP tool errors. More critically, `thread_id` is used to construct git ref paths (e.g., `refs/forge/comments/{thread_id}`). If a malicious or buggy client sends a `thread_id` containing `../` or other path traversal characters, it could write to arbitrary refs. The MCP layer should validate that UUIDs match UUID format and OIDs match hex format before forwarding.